{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646708","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646708"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:34:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:34:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18199"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18199","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18199"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.78,0,0,0.22,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10913"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78415"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10913","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10913"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18199"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63777"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7302"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25371"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25372"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26880"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78415"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EScoliosis is a term used to describe a particular curvature of the spine.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about scoliosis is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Scoliosis is primarily a curvature in the sagittal plane","Scoliosis is most commonly caused by trauma","Scoliosis only affects the lumbar region","Scoliosis can result in wedge-shaped vertebrae","Scoliosis is always associated with pain"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EScoliosis is a condition characterised by an abnormal lateral curvature of the spine. It can result from various causes, including congenital abnormalities, idiopathic factors, or neuromuscular conditions. Here is an example (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe correct statement is that \u003Cstrong\u003Escoliosis can result in wedge-shaped vertebrae\u003C/strong\u003E. This occurs due to uneven growth or deformities in the vertebrae, contributing to the lateral curvature of the spine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScoliosis is primarily a curvature in the sagittal plane\u003C/strong\u003E - Scoliosis is a lateral curvature, not sagittal\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScoliosis is most commonly caused by trauma\u003C/strong\u003E - It is most often idiopathic or due to congenital or neuromuscular factors\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScoliosis only affects the lumbar region\u003C/strong\u003E - It can affect any part of the spine, commonly the thoracic region\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScoliosis is always associated with pain\u003C/strong\u003E - While it can cause pain, not all cases are painful\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Scoliosis is a lateral curvature of the spine that can be caused by congenital, idiopathic, or neuromuscular factors.","The vertebrae in scoliosis may become wedge-shaped due to uneven growth or deformities.","Scoliosis can affect any part of the spine, but it is most commonly seen in the thoracic region."],"references":["Kuznia AL, Hernandez AK, Lee LU. Adolescent Idiopathic Scoliosis: Common Questions and Answers. Am Fam Physician. 2020; 101:19-23"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63777"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18199"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21451"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21451","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21451"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/snIKC57X8AHHFDUEIczMPo8S0iRHYv.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/snIKC57X8AHHFDUEIczMPo8S0iRHYv.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":317,"height":480}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63777"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-10T17:56:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-10T17:56:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10913"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78415"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"hea